<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="44" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,1618,2008]" pageId="1" pageNumber="44">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,295,1618,1644]" pageId="1" pageNumber="44">Etymology:</emphasis>
The generic name is derived from the Latin, 
<emphasis box="[824,876,1619,1644]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="44">Sino</emphasis>
-(Chinese) and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1758" box="[1056,1159,1619,1644]" class="Insecta" family="Panorpidae" genus="Panorpa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mecoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="44" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1056,1159,1619,1644]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="44">Panorpa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(scorpionfly), referring to the new genus related to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1758" box="[473,576,1659,1684]" class="Insecta" family="Panorpidae" genus="Panorpa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mecoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="44" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[473,576,1659,1684]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="44">Panorpa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and endemic to 
<collectingCountry box="[769,843,1659,1685]" name="China" pageId="1" pageNumber="44">China</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="44" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,1618,2008]" pageId="1" pageNumber="44">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,327,1698,1724]" pageId="1" pageNumber="44">Diagnosis:</emphasis>
This new genus can be readily distinguished from 
<taxonomicName authority="Linnaeus" authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1758" box="[927,1143,1699,1725]" class="Insecta" family="Panorpidae" genus="Panorpa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mecoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="44" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[927,1030,1699,1724]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="44">Panorpa</emphasis>
Linnaeus
</taxonomicName>
by the following combination of characters: wing membrane deeply yellow with sooty brown markings; R 
<quantity box="[1159,1201,1739,1769]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.08" pageId="1" pageNumber="44" unit="in" value="2.0">
<subScript attach="left" box="[1159,1167,1755,1769]" fontSize="6" pageId="1" pageNumber="44">2</subScript>
in
</quantity>
wings generally 3- branched; tergum VI of male without anal horn; abdominal segment VII of male much thinner and cylindrical at its basal 1/3, but abruptly thicker dorsad and also cylindrical at its distal 2/3, making the distal part 3 times the basal part in diameter, and forming a rectangular shape between the dorsum of basal part and the anterior face of the distal part; gonostylus in male genitalia very long and slender with a very developed basal lobe, the prominent lobe strongly sclerotized and with two hooks apically; ventral parameres simple, not branched.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="45" pageId="1" pageNumber="44" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,1618,2008]" lastBlockId="2.[151,1436,152,863]" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="45" pageId="1" pageNumber="44">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,352,1981,2007]" pageId="1" pageNumber="44">Description:</emphasis>
Large-sized, forewings about 
<quantity box="[709,836,1982,2008]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.7" metricValueMax="1.8" metricValueMin="1.6" pageId="1" pageNumber="44" unit="mm" value="17.0" valueMax="18.0" valueMin="16.0">16–18 mm</quantity>
long, body usually tawny brown to reddish brown. Rostrum long and slender; 3 ocelli; ocellar triangle black, vertex with a broad blackish transverse band through ocelli between eyes. Pronotum with 12 setae along its anterior margin. A pair of claws serrated with 5–6 teeth. Wings deeply yellow, a black seta at the base of R, R 
<subScript attach="left" box="[902,910,248,262]" fontSize="6" pageId="2" pageNumber="45">2</subScript>
generally 3-branched, 1A joins to the posterior margin of wing far beyond origin of Rs (
<figureCitation box="[713,789,274,300]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="6.[151,255,1844,1868]" captionTargetBox="[188,1398,397,1818]" captionTargetId="figure-149@6.[188,1398,397,1818]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 2. Adults of Sinopanorpa digitiformis sp. nov. A. Male; B. Female." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5231067" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5231067/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="45">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
). Abdomen in both sexes not longer than the wings. Abdominal segments VI–VIII of male elongated; segment VI without anal horn; segment VII peculiar in shape, its basal 1/3 much thinner and cylindrical, but its distal 2/3 abruptly thicker and also cylindrical, making the distal part 3 times as thick as the basal part in diameter, and forming a rectangular shape between the dorsum of basal part and the anterior face of the distal part (
<figureCitation box="[850,941,434,460]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="4.[151,255,1904,1928]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,470,1877]" captionTargetId="figure-189@4.[151,1436,470,1877]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 1. Sinopanorpa tincta (Navas). A–E. Male: A. Male adult, dorsal view; B. Abdomen of male with genital bulb, lateral view; C. Genital bulb, dorsal view; D. Genital bulb with hypovalves, ventral view; E. Genital bulb with hypovalves removed, ventral view. F–I. Female: F. Female adult, dorsal view; G. Subgenital plate, ventral view; H. Internal skeleton, ventral view; I. same, dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5231065" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5231065/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="45">Fig. 1B</figureCitation>
). Male genital bulb long elliptic; gonostylus very long and curved, with peculiar highly sclerotized basal lobe and triangular mesal process; hypovalves long and broad; ventral parameres developed, extending at least beyond the base of gonostylus; ventral parameres quite long, at least reaching the base of gonostylus, not branched.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="45" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,152,863]" pageId="2" pageNumber="45">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,321,594,620]" pageId="2" pageNumber="45">Remarks:</emphasis>
In 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1758" box="[368,470,595,620]" class="Insecta" family="Panorpidae" genus="Panorpa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mecoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="45" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[368,470,595,620]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="45">Panorpa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, very few species also have 3-branched R 
<quantity box="[993,1030,594,625]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.08" pageId="2" pageNumber="45" unit="in" value="2.0">
<subScript attach="left" box="[993,1001,611,625]" fontSize="6" pageId="2" pageNumber="45">2</subScript>
in
</quantity>
wings, such as 
<taxonomicName authority="MacLachlan 1882" authorityName="MacLachlan" authorityYear="1882" class="Insecta" family="Panorpidae" genus="Panorpa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mecoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="45" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hybrida">
<emphasis box="[1231,1436,595,620]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="45">Panorpa hybrida</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="MacLachlan, R." box="[151,364,637,663]" pageId="2" pageNumber="45" pagination="130 - 132" refId="ref7574" refString="MacLachlan, R. (1882) A new European Panorpa. Entomologist's monthly Magazine, 19, 130 - 132." type="journal article" year="1882">MacLachlan 1882</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
from Europe, 
<taxonomicName authority="MacLachlan 1887" authorityName="MacLachlan" authorityYear="1887" box="[539,860,637,663]" class="Insecta" family="Panorpidae" genus="Panorpa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mecoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="45" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lewisi">
<emphasis box="[539,641,638,663]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="45">P. lewisi</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="MacLachlan, R." box="[646,860,637,663]" pageId="2" pageNumber="45" pagination="400 - 406" refId="ref7596" refString="MacLachlan, R. (1887) Descriptions de plusieurs nouvelles especes de Panorpides provenant du Japon et de la Siberie orientale. Mitteilungen der Schweizerischen Entomologischen Gesellschaft, 7, 400 - 406." type="journal article" year="1887">MacLachlan 1887</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Thunberg 1784" authorityName="Thunberg" authorityYear="1784" box="[920,1241,637,663]" class="Insecta" family="Panorpidae" genus="Panorpa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mecoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="45" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="japonica">
<emphasis box="[920,1053,638,663]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="45">P. japonica</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Thunberg, C. P." box="[1061,1241,637,663]" pageId="2" pageNumber="45" pagination="60 - 63" refId="ref7816" refString="Thunberg, C. P. (1784) Dissertation entomologicae novas insectorum species, sistens, cejus partem qvartam, praeses Carol. P. Thunberg, et respondens Carolus P. Engstrom. Upsaliae. Mantis, pp. 60 - 63." type="book chapter" year="1784">Thunberg 1784</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry box="[1316,1385,637,663]" name="Japan" pageId="2" pageNumber="45">Japan</collectingCountry>
, but these species are quite different from the new genus in wing patterns and genital bulb. Based on the shape of the abdominal segments VII-VIII in male, the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="MacLachlan" authorityYear="1894" box="[692,888,718,743]" class="Insecta" family="Panorpidae" genus="Panorpa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mecoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="45" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="diceras">
<emphasis box="[692,888,718,743]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="45">Panorpa diceras</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group in western 
<collectingCountry box="[1099,1169,717,743]" name="China" pageId="2" pageNumber="45">China</collectingCountry>
are also elongated and constricted at basal part (
<bibRefCitation author="Cheng, F. Y." box="[444,599,757,783]" pageId="2" pageNumber="45" pagination="1 - 118" refId="ref7215" refString="Cheng, F. Y. (1957) Revision of the Chinese Mecoptera. Bulletin of the Museum of Comparative Zoology, 116, 1 - 118." type="journal article" year="1957">Cheng, 1957</bibRefCitation>
), but they are distinctive for the two anal horns on the posterior margin of abdominal segment VI, and the ventral parameres 3-branched rather than simple.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[197,1227,837,863]" pageId="2" pageNumber="45" type="distribution">
